title: $A up despite upbeat US services figures
text:
Thu, Aug 6, 2015, 8:17 AM AEST - Australia Markets open in 1 hr 43 mins $A up despite upbeat US services figures AAP â€“ 32 minutes ago Print 
The Australian dollar is higher despite strong US non-manufacturing activity offsetting softer US employment figures. 
At 0700 AEST on Thursday, the currency was trading at 73.56 US cents, up from 73.49 cents on Wednesday. 
ANZ senior manager FX Sam Tuck said the Aussie dollar traded up after payroll firm ADP estimated the US private sector added 185,000 jobs in July, below analysts' estimate for 220,000 additional jobs. 
"That was weaker than expected," he said. 
"But then (the Aussie) traded back down after the ISM non-manufacturing survey, which was a real driver in currency markets overnight." 
The US dollar soared on the American economy's July service sector data, which expanded 4.3 per cent to reach a record high. 
New orders jumped 5.5 percentage points and employment activity advanced a substantial 6.9 percentage points, both reaching their highest levels since August 2005. 
Westpac strategist Imre Speizer predicted greenback strength will weigh on the currency until the local market's highlight later on Thursday, Australia's unemployment figures for July. 
CURRENCY SNAPSHOT AT 0700 AEST ON THURSDAY 
One Australian dollar buys: 
* 73.56 US cents, from 73.49 cents on Wednesday 
* 91.85 Japanese yen, from 91.41 yen 
* 67.45 euro cents, from 67.59 euro cents 
* 112.98 New Zealand cents, from 112.59 NZ cents 
* 47.15 British pence, from 47.23 pence 
(*Currency closes taken at 1700 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
